":"about 1560","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","1523":"1523","1501":"1501","1520":"1520","1561":"1561","1560":"1560","1607":"1607","1490":"1490","1528":"1528","1549":"1549","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","York, York district, North Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"York, Yorkshire, England","Yorkshire East Riding, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire East Riding, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rotherford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of English   Rutherford  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Rutherford","meanings":["Scottish and northern English: habitational name from Rutherford in Maxton (Roxburghshire), apparently named with Old English <i>hrīther</i>, <i>hrȳther</i> ‘ox’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’, though a British Celtic origin of the type <i>ro-</i> ‘great’ + <i>dubr-</i> ‘water, river’ is also possible for the first element. Places named <i>Rutherford</i> in West Linton (West Lothian) and Barningham (North Yorkshire) are less likely sources of the name."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":26,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705202,"age":35,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Alexander Rotherford was born in 1523, in Yorkshire, England, his father, Thomas Rotherforth, was 33 and his mother, Lady Margaret Selby, was 23. He married Mrs. Alexander Rotherforth about 1560. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died in 1561, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 38."},"et":{"1523–1561":"1523–1561","1528–Female":"1528–Surnud","1560–Female":"1560–Surnud","1561–1607":"1561–1607","1490–1523":"1490–1523","1501–1535":"1501–1535","Abt 1560":"umbes 1560","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","1523":"1523","1501":"1501","1520":"1520","1561":"1561","1560":"1560","1607":"1607","1490":"1490","1528":"1528","1549":"1549","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","York, York district, North Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"York, Yorkshire, England","Yorkshire East Riding, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire East Riding, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1523–1561":"1523–1561","1528–Female":"1528–Kuollut","1560–Female":"1560–Kuollut"